# Ident (RFC 1413, tcp:113) server USERID reply. The ident server (src port 113) answers the query with a
# single US-ASCII line "6193, 23 : USERID : UNIX : stjohns\r\n": the same two ports, the reply type
# USERID, the operating-system token UNIX, and the owning user name "stjohns", terminated by CR LF. The
# whole payload is kept verbatim (byte-perfect); the first line is parsed for display into
# {isQuery:false, responseType:"USERID", serverPort:6193, clientPort:23, opsys:"UNIX", userId:"stjohns"}.
# source: CONSTRUCTED — the reply line is a spec-accurate RFC 1413 USERID response (the example user is
# from the RFC); the eth+ipv4+tcp envelope (172.17.0.2:113 -> 172.17.0.1:49798) was synthesized by the
# netkitty encoder so checksums/lengths are valid. tshark 4.6.7 in this environment ships no RFC 1413
# Ident dissector (verified: "ident" is not a valid tcp.port protocol), so it labels the payload
# eth:ip:tcp:data; the frame is nonetheless a valid Ident-on-113 message. Verified [eth,ipv4,tcp,ident]
# decode + byte-perfect round-trip via new Codec([Ident]).
# byte breakdown: 14 eth | 20 ipv4 (proto 6) | 20 tcp (srcport 0x0071=113) | 36 ident payload
